segments.text: How was it that Dr. Suttle was involved?
Well, Dr. Suttle was involved.
He was fairly active in the cyclotron project.
More detail end up with that.
We went into the arts and science.
Dr. Sowell and Mr. Ruddard used him primarily for his research know-how.
He built our research programs here university-wide, not just engineering, and also to assess people.
He used to sit in on all of the places we used.
It was out of the value of commanding the system.
which is almost entirely from the research point of view, which is why I didn't mind one thing or give it to some of the other fellows who had responsibility for the education side of things.
But Suttle was the advocate of research, technically.
Now there are lots of stories that float around about the psychotron and the funding for the psychotron.
One of them I've heard that I don't, I wonder if there's a myth in that, is that Princeton was supposed to get the money and Princeton already had a bulldog for it.
Is that a mere myth?
I don't think it was Princeton, I think it was Maryland.
We in Maryland were essentially competitors and we got the money.
And really it's been a very useful instrument.
Shortly after we brought it here, of course, they determined that this was a useful device for treating cancer.
So we worked, you know, for years with the MD Anderson people in Houston.
One of our young men in nuclear engineering.
at UCLA now.
We developed the procedures for determining the dose rates required to treat people and essentially we developed that procedure.
Now of course it's much more sophisticated now.
Most of the major cancer facilities have their own beam machines, not all of them are cyclotrons that they use for treatment.
for the work actually.
Didn't radiation therapy go on, research go on here even in the 50s?
We were big in that.
That's one I forgot.
We were very big in radiation research.

Right after World War II, Sidney Brown, who was a biologist, did most of his work in the engineering sperm stations, but we were the only people who were really supporting and encouraging to get on with this.
And then we used to do a lot of these work with Spanish goats.
We kept those Spanish goats out there right next to the nuclear science center.
And that old facility is still out there.
It's not used to it, but you can see it.
It's pretty well fallen down due to the wooden construction.
Sidney Brown, at one time, was probably one of the leading experts in this country in radiation protection.
Is this the same type of research that has been going on in the 60s with the medical radiation therapy?
I suppose they were joined together sometime, but not here.
If that joining was done, it was probably not going to be answered.
George Price was the last man.
I don't know if you've run into Price or not.
George Price was the last man that we had in the radiation biology area.
Of course, that sort of...
research has not been done much in recent years.
What year, or approximately what year was it that you got the MD Anderson and the Keys got together?
I would guess it was sometime in the 70s, early 70s.
I don't think we did, did we?
Maybe we did.

So I would guess that work started even in 69 or 70.
Well, it started pretty quickly after we had the cyclotron.
Which of the many projects that CASE has started since you've been here are you most proud of being involved in?
I don't know.
I enjoyed all of the work that we did.
It's really hard to say.
I suppose that the work that I'm most proud of actually is the highway safety research work that we started for the Transportation Institute.
Because I was almost directly responsible for getting that started.
A lot of people said we couldn't do it.
We began that work back in the early 63.
and the breakaway signs and the impact attenuators that have been built on highways around this country have saved lots of people's lives.
And those are all developed here?
Those are all developed here.
You can find lots of people playing a responsibility for it later in the year.
We know where it all came from.
And unfortunately we didn't happen to be able to see it.
It was all done in the open area.
Oil shortage in the mid-70s affected research.
Yes.
When the oil shortage came along, it was pretty obvious that ultimately there had to be a replacement for petroleum.
And it's still true.
Ultimately, we've got it.
So we began then to take a look at what are alternate fuels that you can use to replace petroleum.
Of course when you do that you begin to look at the fuels that you can get from coal, from renewable resources like wood and plant materials and that sort of thing.
So we started with our

organ fuels program and a chemical engineering people that developed a system that was able to run the standard automobile that was sold in this country on methanol, methyl alcohol, and that was successful.
We started a program in which we were trying to
Recovered gas from late night by burning it in the ground.
That wasn't very successful.
And we took a look at a lot of other things like flurry suspension of the coal, other ways of burning coal.
We did quite a wide variety of research.

No.

Have you had any changes in your attitude over time?
Looking back, when you first took the job, his is still the same, and his goals are still the same.
No, I haven't changed my mind about what we ought to do.
goals we have to try to reach.
Essentially a two-fold goal, to carry on activities which would be important in the state of Texas and to contribute to the educational programs here in Indiana.
We work from time to time with a lot of other programs besides this.
I would ask your opinion on a definition that is often argued over, the difference between pure science and technology.
What they generally say is that if you look at the basics of what you call pure science,
done for no good reason except just to know what's going on.
We have to know what the facts are.
Whereas most applied research is all technology, I guess.
It really has a basic goal.
It's an alternative fuel project.
We started out with the idea that methanol was probably our best
fuel the standpoint of competitiveness economics.
And that if we were going to be forced to use it, that we'd have to take the automobiles right off the street and convert them.
And we did that successfully.
That's very much applied to .
Is there any other, are there any other projects that I haven't asked you about?
Well, there probably are some.
I know there are others.
Don't want to be an old man like I am just to slip you by.
One thing I'd like to ask you is what is your exact title?
Exact title?
Well, I'm Dean Emeritus.
Okay.
I'm working part-time for the
and for them, I'm a research engineer.
Well, I had read that you retired in 1980, was it?
Yeah, 1980.
But you maintained your connections with the Research Foundation?
I stayed on with the Research Foundation because I felt I had not really done for them what I should.
And they paid part of my salary.
No, I was over there two years.
I had several connections with them in 82.
Last year I didn't do anything.
I didn't get paid.
This year I'm working on a project.
Are you working on a particular project for them?
No, I generally work on taking a look at things.
We ought to be doing it or not.
We ought to quit or that sort of thing.
And in that general direction, how has TEAS established over the years what projects are ready to die?
Well, that's a tough question.
That's, of course, the hardest question of all of them.
We need to reach the point where it's been worthwhile for any more time than that would do it for us.
You may have heard there's a plan going on right now about nuclear weapons, what we ought to do about it.
The time has come when those decisions are going to have to be made.
The American people are very scared to death of having any sort of nuclear involvements, power, what have you.
So it looks like this is something that really may not be worthwhile doing at this time.
Take a look at it and see whether or not this is the time to abandon it.
We did a lot of work here in the early years of our nuclear program in an area we called Activation Analysis.
But that's still going on here in the Department of Chemistry.
But we decided, for our purposes, that we had reached the end of the line, and we transferred the program to chemistry, and they changed it to a much more fun little type program.
In terms of administration, in the late 50s, Teas also became administrator of
The data processing center and all those, is this a purely administrative function or?
No.
Why was this, why?
The reason we were in the computer business is because we were the only ones that would do it.
We were the only ones that could do it.
Yeah, the experiment station, a very small 5DM machine in our direction.
That said, I do not think it applies for us to put any more of our research into this arena than we have now.
We cannot support the education program, research programs, and engineering as much as we can.
So, if there's going to be anything more sophisticated around here, somebody else is going to take it up.
So we decided that we would see what we could do to produce the next processing program that would serve our engineering people and would also serve the college generally.
It was actually a borrowed money.
And we would buy the IBM 650, which was a working machine that we had.
and we built the warden building and the processing center building over there.

It wouldn't have gotten better.

and has come up with the agreements with NTRM and that type of thing.

And we were too successful in those operations.

Is there anything else you'd like to add?
Offhand, I don't think, but it's been pretty well covered.
It's been tough getting all that together, but it's been very informative.
Well, I think the injury experimentation is going to be a great contribution to the story, and a great contribution to the state of Texas.
The country is facing a lot of problems, and we're having a little more jealousy than we used to.
So we can do what we have to do to get things done.
That's my answer.
Thank you.
